There are many reasons why older specimens representing new species remain undetected and undescribed in herbaria. In many cases, herbaria are overloaded and specimens are unprocessed and unavailable for study; expertise in particular taxa is often lacking, so new species are unnoticed, misplaced, or assigned to unidentified material at the end of each family. Some specimens are incomplete or lack flowers or fruits (
7
). In addition, specimens are sometimes identified as new species, annotated, and even given manuscript names but never described and published.

